V29.0132; V18.0780; V41.0770                  Comparative Imperialism: The Post Colonial Turn         Majithia         Mon/Wed 3:30-4:45, 4 pts.         V29.0811; V18.0813.001; V40.0252         In postcolonial studies, debates regarding representation and  revolution intersect in understandings of: colonialism; nationalism;  questions of identity, alterity, hybridity and origins within contexts  of gender; race; class; sexuality; subaltern historiography; and the  role of the academy in the world. Often responses to universalizing  projects of modernity and progress re-invent linguistic and literary  forms through the use of “broken English” in, pidgin, creole,  multi-lingual, and “rotten” forms among others while cinema creates an  “aesthetics of garbage,” Third Cinema, or “an aesthetics of hunger” to  imagine vernacular modernity. This course examines questions of form  and historical, political, and cultural context by focusing on British  metropolitan and Caribbean, South Asian, and African postcolonial and  with the question of whether the “postcolonial turn” has given way to  “the global turn.” Our comparative study may include texts by: Achebe,  Ali, Conrad, Devi, Forster, Gandhi, Rushdie, Saleh, Saro-Wiwa; films by  Furtado, Pontecorvo, Sembene; and selections from the writings of  Anderson, Bhabha, Fanon, Said, and Spivak. Sheetal Majithia is an Assistant Professor of Literature at NYU Abu Dhabi. She received her B.A. in English and Middle East and Asian Languages and Civilizations from Columbia University (1994) and her Ph.D. in Comparative Literature, with concentrations in feminist, gender, and sexuality studies and in South Asian studies from Cornell University (2009). Previously, she was an Andrew W. Mellon Teaching Fellow at the University of Pennsylvania and a Visiting Assistant Professor of World Literature at the School of Humanities , Arts, and Cultural Studies at Hampshire College . Her teaching interests include theories of modernity, globalization, comparative postcolonial literature, film, feminist studies and South Asian literature, film, and popular culture.                   Topics in 20th Century Literature:         Rethinking Secularism Through Global Fiction         Majithia         Mon/Wed 4:45-6:10, 4 pts.         V29.0190.002; V90.0190.001; V77.0191.001; V40.0190.001               Globalization, or the acceleration of transportation and information  technologies, promises anew era in which space exceeds time to re-configure  understanding of experience and geopolitical conditions. Changing human  geographies and migration prompt a re-configuration of social, political, and  representational practices, particularly “practices of the imagination” so that  questions of citizenship, national identity, and belonging are fore grounded  and new spatial and temporal references emerge. In public discourses about  globalization, for example, we see the re-consideration of concepts such  secular and sacred; reason and the irrational; civilization and barbarism; and  modernity and tradition. Debates about these questions have been raised in the  context of literary representations for quite some time through matters of  censorship, translation, and adaptation. This course will survey recent debates  on globalization and its discontents with particular attention to re-evaluation  of the licenses and limits of secularism as a guarantor of pluralism, human  rights, democracy, and critique by drawing on works by: Abu- Lughod ,   Asad , Appadurai , Brown, Butler , Connolly Foucault,  Jameson, Mahmood , Mufti, and Warner. Our readings  will draw on global fictions—often censored or deemed controversial—that map  social horizons of modernity through formal innovation by authors including  Leila Abouleila , Monica Ali, Lindsey Collen , Amitav Ghosh , Graham Greene, Orhan Pamuk , Salman Rushdie, and Marjane Satrapi .                   Classics in the Middle Ages & Renaissance: Doubtful Knowing: Skepticism and the Transformation of the Early Modern World         Ramachandran         Tues 12:30-3:15, 4 pts.         V29.0425          The early modern period is frequently characterized as marking a moment of “epistemic rupture,” a transition of dramatic proportions during which the grounds of what constituted certain knowledge changed. Several fundamental questions emerge as a consequence: how do we know something is true? When is it legitimate to question our beliefs about cherished values, morals, and assumptions about the order of the world? How does the intuition of radical uncertainty create new ethical dilemmas? And most central to our concerns: how do we describe the new literature that emerges to assuage the anxieties of doubt? This course traces and interrogates these questions by examining the intersections between Renaissance literature and the history of skepticism (broadly defined) – that is, the phenomenon of questioning our knowledge in many, if not all, domains in which we ordinarily think knowledge is possible. We will cast a wide net, ranging from cosmographies and travel accounts of New World discoveries, to the discovery of new planets and new scientific systems; from fictional utopias and imagined worlds to problems of philosophic truth and political action; and from Reformation and Counter-Reformation polemics to the new, hybrid interpretations of Genesis. The emphasis will be on developing a literary history of skeptical knowing across disciplines and genres in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. Consequently, we will read deeply and widely in texts from the period as well as their classical predecessors, and will refer to secondary criticism only as appropriate. Texts will include works by: Plato, Sextus Empiricus, Cicero, Lucretius; Columbus, Vespucci, Erasmus, Machiavelli, Ariosto, More, Montaigne, Bruno, Marlowe, Spenser, Shakespeare, Galileo, Kepler, Descartes, Hobbes, and Milton. Students are strongly encouraged to read at least some texts in the original languages.         Ayesha Ramachandran received her BA from Smith  College and her PhD in Renaissance Studies from Yale University. Her  research and teaching focus on the literature, philosophy and cultural  history of early modern Europe. She has been fascinated by imagined  lands, global connections, and networks of exchange in the sixteenth  and seventeenth centuries – concerns that coalesce in her current book  project that traces the renovation of “the world” as an idea, a  concept, and a system of order between 1580 and 1700. Her wide-ranging  interests include the history of ideas, especially political theory and  aesthetics (from 1500-1750); history of science and philosophy  (Montaigne to Leibniz); contemporary philosophy and postcolonial  theory. She has published articles on Elizabethan poetry and early  modern natural philosophy, on Renaissance epic and romance, and on  postcolonial drama. She was awarded a Junior Fellowship at the Harvard  Society of Fellows in 2007 and is currently an assistant professor in  the department of English at Stony Brook University.                  Introduction to Comp Lit:         Scoring Literature: The Drug Culture         Ronell         Thurs 3:30-6:10, 4 pts.         V29.0116.001 ; V51.0116.001          As a way to get access to some of the most vital aspects of  comparative literature as a field, this course will explore the role of  addiction, pharmacology, intoxication, and poison in fiction,  philosophy, and psychoanalysis. Our readings will take us to places  where the motifs linked to drug cultures are often concealed or  repressed. During the course of the semester we will take a close look  at the pharmacodependency with which literature has been associated  historically--as sedative, as cure, as escape conduit or euphorizing  substance, as mimetic poisoning. In the cases of Baudelaire, Flaubert  and James Joyce the literary text was legally treated as a drug and run  off the market by outraged judges. We will analyze the legal documents  that first declared these literary works illicit, and then turned  around those decisions.         Some of the questions that will be raised in class  discussion include: What is the relation of literature to law? How does  the literary work become a medical problem? Why has fiction been  identified as part of a self-destructive drive? What are the rhetorical  strategies that render the poetic word, since the time of Plato,  socially inadmissible? We will read the relevant stimulants and works  of Kant, Heidegger, Derrida in philosophy, Freud and Lacan on  destructive pleasure, and explore the terrains opened up by Thomas De  Quincey's "Confessions of an Opium Eater" to Flaubert's "Madame  Bovary," and Boroughs' and Dennis Coopers' works to see how imaginary  worlds collide with acts of legal and social policing. Prepare for the  intellectual rush of a lifetime!            Plus Recitation         V29.0116.002,V51.0116.002 : Tues 3:30-4:45 Cole         V29.0116.003, V51.0116.003: Tues 4:55-6:10 Cole         V29.0116.004, V51.0116.004: Fri 11:00-12:15 Kramer         V29.0116.005, V51.0116.005: Fri 12:30-1:45 Rauscher  Topics in 20th Century Literature: Prison Literature         Sanders   Wed 11:00-1:45, 4 pts.     V29.0190     “The writer destroys time.” So writes Breyten Breytenbach in his classic prison memoir, True Confessions of an Albino Terrorist .  Punishment by deprivation of freedom, imprisonment imposes unusual  constraints on the writer. Prison writing, accordingly, registers the  profound effects on the imagination of sensory and mental deprivation,  isolation, as well as the unusual social organization of prisons. In  addition to these factors, restrictions and conditions—ranging from  outright prohibition to confiscation and censorship—are in many cases  placed on writing by prisoners. In this course we will explore the  responses of a variety of writers, most of them political prisoners, to  incarceration in fiction and non-fiction. Our principal areas of focus  will be writing from the Nazi concentration camps of World War Two, the  Russian gulags, the prisons of apartheid South Africa, and the jails of  American Civil Rights era and the “War on Terror.” Authors may include,  among others, Henry David Thoreau, Fyodor Dostoevsky, Primo Levi,  Charlotte Delbo, Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn, Varlam Shalamov, Breyten  Breytenbach, Ruth First, Martin Luther King, Jr., and George Jackson.  Theoretical writing from Michel Foucault and others.    Studies in Prose Genres: Autobiography    Sieburth   Tues/Thurs 11:00-12:15, 4 pts.     V29.0125     The word Autobiography can be etymologically decomposed into: autos (“self”) + bios (“life”) + graphê (“writing”),  and over the course of the semester we will be looking at the  interaction of these three elements as the genre of autobiography  evolves over time. Until the 20th century, autobiography has been, for  the most, a predominantly Western practice—for very specific religious  and cultural reasons which we shall explore and which have to do with  the particular constructions of the “self” associated with the  Judeo-Christian tradition. Examples of autobiographical writing,  however, can also be found in classical Chinese and Japanese cultures,  and we shall accordingly examine a few samples of these at the outset  of the course by reading a few short Confucian autobiographies,  selections from The Pillow Book of Sei Shonagan , and Shen Fu’s Six Records of a Floating Life . We will then turn our attention to the Confessions of St. Augustine, a conversion narrative which in many ways provides the   master-text of Western autobiography. This will be followed by another  Christian “Life,” the earliest known text of its sort in vernacular  English, the 15th-century Book of Margery Kempe . Selections from Montaigne’s Essays   will then be placed against this religious tradition of autobiography:  emphasis will be laid not only on the more secularized or “humanist”  notions of the self emerging during the Renaissance, but on the  essay-form itself as providing a non-narrative model for  self-portraiture. From Montaigne, we will turn to Puritan and early  Republican America, represented by the “captivity narrative” of Mary  Rowlandson and by Ben Franklin’s slippery account of his  self-fashioning into celebrity. This will lead into a reading of the  first six books of Rousseau’s Confessions , which rewrite  Augustine while setting the agenda for the next two centuries of modern  autobiography. Equally influential, at least insofar as the African  American literary tradition is concerned, is the Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass ,  which blends elements of the sentimental novel and the European  picaresque into a call for political self-liberation through writing.   The final unit of the course will focus on the impact of psychiatry and  psychoanalysis on modern autobiography: the texts include Aurélia , Gérard de Nerval’s account of his descent into “madness,” Michel Leiris’s post-surrealist Manhood , and the poet H.D.’s account of her analysis in Vienna with the master himself, Tribute to Freud .    Note: Course enrollment limited to 20. Requirements: Four short papers (5-7pp.) over the course of the semester.                  Junior Theory Seminar in Comp Lit: The Frankfurt School         Zhang         Mon 12:30-3:15, 4 pts.         V29.0200          This seminar introduces the student to the basic writings of the  Frankfurt School, also known as “Critical Social Theory,” that  constitutes a major component of Western Marxism in the 20th century.   Instead of a scholastic treatment of the history and themes of this  school, the seminar starts with some of its most popular, provocative,  and controversial figures and arguments that helped define  intellectually the heydays of the Global Sixties, such as Marcuse and  Fromm with their propositions on freedom, autonomy, eros, and revolt,  and then works its way “backwards” into the school’s historical,  philosophical, and political conditions and premises as they are  formulated during inter-war years by its more “difficult” authors such  as Horkheimer, Adorno, Benjamin, Korsch and Lukacs. In this  retrospective reading, the seminar seeks to inspire the student to  reflect simultaneously on the “end” of Frankfurt School in its  normative thinking developed during the latter days of the Cold War  (Habermas) as well as on its moral and philosophical origins in the  aftermath of WWI which seem to maintain their critical edge,  intellectual energy, and political poignancy vis-à-vis our current age  of intensified, globalized capitalist logic in every domain of social  life.   Requirement includes a one-page weekly reading response and a 10pp term paper.       A tentative reading list:   -Adorno, T.W. & Max Horkheimer, Dialectic of Enlightenment;    -Adono: from Minima Moralia;   -Benjamin, Walter, “On Some Motifs of Baudelaire”; “Work of Art in the  Age of Mechanical Reproducibility”; “Thesis on Philosophy of History”;    -Fromm, Erich, Escape From Freedom;    -Habermas, J., from Knowledge and Human Interests; Theory and Practice; and Legitimation Crisis;    -Korsch, from Marxism and Philosophy    -Lukacs, George, from The Theory of the Novel; and from History and Class Consciousness    -Marcuse, Herbert: Reason and Revolution; Eros and Civilization; One Dimensional Man; and The Aesthetic Dimension                  Back to Top                     Contact us | © New York University , Arts and Science

In this  retrospective reading, the seminar seeks to inspire the student to  reflect simultaneously on the “end” of Frankfurt School in its  normative thinking developed during the latter days of the Cold War  (Habermas) as well as on its moral and philosophical origins in the  aftermath of WWI which seem to maintain their critical edge,  intellectual energy, and political poignancy vis-à-vis our current age  of intensified, globalized capitalist logic in every domain of social  life.   Requirement includes a one-page weekly reading response and a 10pp term paper. Majithia, Assistant Professor of Literature, NYUAD                                                      Sheetal Majithia                  Assistant Professor of Literature                                Affiliation: NYU Abu Dhabi                                                 Biography      Sheetal Majithia’s research and teaching focuses on theories of modernity; globalization; comparative post-colonial literature, film, feminist, gender, and sexuality studies; cultural studies; and South Asian studies. She was the recipient of several fellowships and travel awards while a doctoral student at Cornell University, and won the university’s Beatrice Brown Award for work on women and gender.   She is the author of “Of Foreigners and Fetishes: A Reading of Recent South Asian American Fiction” in the South Asian Magazine for Action and Reflection. Majithia has also won awards for creative writing and participated in the prestigious Breadloaf writers’ workshop at Middlebury College in Vermont. Majithia has recently taught courses such as “Imaging India,” “The Postcolonial Turn,” “Global Traffic,” and “Melodrama and Modernity,” which reflect her disciplinary range.   At NYU Abu Dhabi, she teaches a core curriculum course in world literature, as well as courses on postcolonial literature and the cultures of globalization. Previously, she was an Andrew W. Mellon Teaching Fellow at the University of Pennsylvania and a visiting assistant professor of World Literature at the School of Humanities, Arts, and Cultural Studies at Hampshire College in Amherst, MA. Majithia earned her Ph.D. in Comparative Literature, with concentrations in feminist, gender, and sexuality studies and in South Asian studies from Cornell University, and her B.A. in English and Middle East and Asian Languages and Civilizations from Columbia University. V29.0132; V18.0780; V41.0770                  Comparative Imperialism: The Post Colonial Turn         Majithia         Mon/Wed 3:30-4:45, 4 pts.         V29.0811; V18.0813.001; V40.0252         In postcolonial studies, debates regarding representation and  revolution intersect in understandings of: colonialism; nationalism;  questions of identity, alterity, hybridity and origins within contexts  of gender; race; class; sexuality; subaltern historiography; and the  role of the academy in the world. Often responses to universalizing  projects of modernity and progress re-invent linguistic and literary  forms through the use of “broken English” in, pidgin, creole,  multi-lingual, and “rotten” forms among others while cinema creates an  “aesthetics of garbage,” Third Cinema, or “an aesthetics of hunger” to  imagine vernacular modernity. This course examines questions of form  and historical, political, and cultural context by focusing on British  metropolitan and Caribbean, South Asian, and African postcolonial and  with the question of whether the “postcolonial turn” has given way to  “the global turn.” Our comparative study may include texts by: Achebe,  Ali, Conrad, Devi, Forster, Gandhi, Rushdie, Saleh, Saro-Wiwa; films by  Furtado, Pontecorvo, Sembene; and selections from the writings of  Anderson, Bhabha, Fanon, Said, and Spivak. Sheetal Majithia is an Assistant Professor of Literature at NYU Abu Dhabi. She received her B.A. in English and Middle East and Asian Languages and Civilizations from Columbia University (1994) and her Ph.D. in Comparative Literature, with concentrations in feminist, gender, and sexuality studies and in South Asian studies from Cornell University (2009). Previously, she was an Andrew W. Mellon Teaching Fellow at the University of Pennsylvania and a Visiting Assistant Professor of World Literature at the School of Humanities , Arts, and Cultural Studies at Hampshire College . Her teaching interests include theories of modernity, globalization, comparative postcolonial literature, film, feminist studies and South Asian literature, film, and popular culture.                   Topics in 20th Century Literature:         Rethinking Secularism Through Global Fiction         Majithia         Mon/Wed 4:45-6:10, 4 pts.         V29.0190.002; V90.0190.001; V77.0191.001; V40.0190.001               Globalization, or the acceleration of transportation and information  technologies, promises anew era in which space exceeds time to re-configure  understanding of experience and geopolitical conditions. Changing human  geographies and migration prompt a re-configuration of social, political, and  representational practices, particularly “practices of the imagination” so that  questions of citizenship, national identity, and belonging are fore grounded  and new spatial and temporal references emerge. In public discourses about  globalization, for example, we see the re-consideration of concepts such  secular and sacred; reason and the irrational; civilization and barbarism; and  modernity and tradition. Debates about these questions have been raised in the  context of literary representations for quite some time through matters of  censorship, translation, and adaptation. This course will survey recent debates  on globalization and its discontents with particular attention to re-evaluation  of the licenses and limits of secularism as a guarantor of pluralism, human  rights, democracy, and critique by drawing on works by: Abu- Lughod ,   Asad , Appadurai , Brown, Butler , Connolly Foucault,  Jameson, Mahmood , Mufti, and Warner. Our readings  will draw on global fictions—often censored or deemed controversial—that map  social horizons of modernity through formal innovation by authors including  Leila Abouleila , Monica Ali, Lindsey Collen , Amitav Ghosh , Graham Greene, Orhan Pamuk , Salman Rushdie, and Marjane Satrapi .                   Classics in the Middle Ages & Renaissance: Doubtful Knowing: Skepticism and the Transformation of the Early Modern World         Ramachandran         Tues 12:30-3:15, 4 pts.         V29.0425          The early modern period is frequently characterized as marking a moment of “epistemic rupture,” a transition of dramatic proportions during which the grounds of what constituted certain knowledge changed. Several fundamental questions emerge as a consequence: how do we know something is true? When is it legitimate to question our beliefs about cherished values, morals, and assumptions about the order of the world? How does the intuition of radical uncertainty create new ethical dilemmas? And most central to our concerns: how do we describe the new literature that emerges to assuage the anxieties of doubt? This course traces and interrogates these questions by examining the intersections between Renaissance literature and the history of skepticism (broadly defined) – that is, the phenomenon of questioning our knowledge in many, if not all, domains in which we ordinarily think knowledge is possible. We will cast a wide net, ranging from cosmographies and travel accounts of New World discoveries, to the discovery of new planets and new scientific systems; from fictional utopias and imagined worlds to problems of philosophic truth and political action; and from Reformation and Counter-Reformation polemics to the new, hybrid interpretations of Genesis. The emphasis will be on developing a literary history of skeptical knowing across disciplines and genres in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries. Consequently, we will read deeply and widely in texts from the period as well as their classical predecessors, and will refer to secondary criticism only as appropriate. Texts will include works by: Plato, Sextus Empiricus, Cicero, Lucretius; Columbus, Vespucci, Erasmus, Machiavelli, Ariosto, More, Montaigne, Bruno, Marlowe, Spenser, Shakespeare, Galileo, Kepler, Descartes, Hobbes, and Milton. Students are strongly encouraged to read at least some texts in the original languages.         Ayesha Ramachandran received her BA from Smith  College and her PhD in Renaissance Studies from Yale University. Her  research and teaching focus on the literature, philosophy and cultural  history of early modern Europe. She has been fascinated by imagined  lands, global connections, and networks of exchange in the sixteenth  and seventeenth centuries – concerns that coalesce in her current book  project that traces the renovation of “the world” as an idea, a  concept, and a system of order between 1580 and 1700. Her wide-ranging  interests include the history of ideas, especially political theory and  aesthetics (from 1500-1750); history of science and philosophy  (Montaigne to Leibniz); contemporary philosophy and postcolonial  theory. She has published articles on Elizabethan poetry and early  modern natural philosophy, on Renaissance epic and romance, and on  postcolonial drama. She was awarded a Junior Fellowship at the Harvard  Society of Fellows in 2007 and is currently an assistant professor in  the department of English at Stony Brook University.                  Introduction to Comp Lit:         Scoring Literature: The Drug Culture         Ronell         Thurs 3:30-6:10, 4 pts.         V29.0116.001 ; V51.0116.001          As a way to get access to some of the most vital aspects of  comparative literature as a field, this course will explore the role of  addiction, pharmacology, intoxication, and poison in fiction,  philosophy, and psychoanalysis. Our readings will take us to places  where the motifs linked to drug cultures are often concealed or  repressed. During the course of the semester we will take a close look  at the pharmacodependency with which literature has been associated  historically--as sedative, as cure, as escape conduit or euphorizing  substance, as mimetic poisoning. In the cases of Baudelaire, Flaubert  and James Joyce the literary text was legally treated as a drug and run  off the market by outraged judges. We will analyze the legal documents  that first declared these literary works illicit, and then turned  around those decisions.         Some of the questions that will be raised in class  discussion include: What is the relation of literature to law? How does  the literary work become a medical problem? Why has fiction been  identified as part of a self-destructive drive? What are the rhetorical  strategies that render the poetic word, since the time of Plato,  socially inadmissible? We will read the relevant stimulants and works  of Kant, Heidegger, Derrida in philosophy, Freud and Lacan on  destructive pleasure, and explore the terrains opened up by Thomas De  Quincey's "Confessions of an Opium Eater" to Flaubert's "Madame  Bovary," and Boroughs' and Dennis Coopers' works to see how imaginary  worlds collide with acts of legal and social policing. Prepare for the  intellectual rush of a lifetime!            Plus Recitation         V29.0116.002,V51.0116.002 : Tues 3:30-4:45 Cole         V29.0116.003, V51.0116.003: Tues 4:55-6:10 Cole         V29.0116.004, V51.0116.004: Fri 11:00-12:15 Kramer         V29.0116.005, V51.0116.005: Fri 12:30-1:45 Rauscher  Topics in 20th Century Literature: Prison Literature         Sanders   Wed 11:00-1:45, 4 pts.     V29.0190     “The writer destroys time.” So writes Breyten Breytenbach in his classic prison memoir, True Confessions of an Albino Terrorist .  Punishment by deprivation of freedom, imprisonment imposes unusual  constraints on the writer. Prison writing, accordingly, registers the  profound effects on the imagination of sensory and mental deprivation,  isolation, as well as the unusual social organization of prisons. In  addition to these factors, restrictions and conditions—ranging from  outright prohibition to confiscation and censorship—are in many cases  placed on writing by prisoners. In this course we will explore the  responses of a variety of writers, most of them political prisoners, to  incarceration in fiction and non-fiction. Our principal areas of focus  will be writing from the Nazi concentration camps of World War Two, the  Russian gulags, the prisons of apartheid South Africa, and the jails of  American Civil Rights era and the “War on Terror.” Authors may include,  among others, Henry David Thoreau, Fyodor Dostoevsky, Primo Levi,  Charlotte Delbo, Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn, Varlam Shalamov, Breyten  Breytenbach, Ruth First, Martin Luther King, Jr., and George Jackson.  Theoretical writing from Michel Foucault and others.    Studies in Prose Genres: Autobiography    Sieburth   Tues/Thurs 11:00-12:15, 4 pts.     V29.0125     The word Autobiography can be etymologically decomposed into: autos (“self”) + bios (“life”) + graphê (“writing”),  and over the course of the semester we will be looking at the  interaction of these three elements as the genre of autobiography  evolves over time. Until the 20th century, autobiography has been, for  the most, a predominantly Western practice—for very specific religious  and cultural reasons which we shall explore and which have to do with  the particular constructions of the “self” associated with the  Judeo-Christian tradition. Examples of autobiographical writing,  however, can also be found in classical Chinese and Japanese cultures,  and we shall accordingly examine a few samples of these at the outset  of the course by reading a few short Confucian autobiographies,  selections from The Pillow Book of Sei Shonagan , and Shen Fu’s Six Records of a Floating Life . We will then turn our attention to the Confessions of St. Augustine, a conversion narrative which in many ways provides the   master-text of Western autobiography. This will be followed by another  Christian “Life,” the earliest known text of its sort in vernacular  English, the 15th-century Book of Margery Kempe . Selections from Montaigne’s Essays   will then be placed against this religious tradition of autobiography:  emphasis will be laid not only on the more secularized or “humanist”  notions of the self emerging during the Renaissance, but on the  essay-form itself as providing a non-narrative model for  self-portraiture. From Montaigne, we will turn to Puritan and early  Republican America, represented by the “captivity narrative” of Mary  Rowlandson and by Ben Franklin’s slippery account of his  self-fashioning into celebrity. This will lead into a reading of the  first six books of Rousseau’s Confessions , which rewrite  Augustine while setting the agenda for the next two centuries of modern  autobiography. Equally influential, at least insofar as the African  American literary tradition is concerned, is the Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass ,  which blends elements of the sentimental novel and the European  picaresque into a call for political self-liberation through writing.   The final unit of the course will focus on the impact of psychiatry and  psychoanalysis on modern autobiography: the texts include Aurélia , Gérard de Nerval’s account of his descent into “madness,” Michel Leiris’s post-surrealist Manhood , and the poet H.D.’s account of her analysis in Vienna with the master himself, Tribute to Freud .    Note: Course enrollment limited to 20. Requirements: Four short papers (5-7pp.) over the course of the semester. She was the recipient of several fellowships and travel awards while a doctoral student at Cornell University, and won the university’s Beatrice Brown Award for work on women and gender.   She is the author of “Of Foreigners and Fetishes: A Reading of Recent South Asian American Fiction” in the South Asian Magazine for Action and Reflection. Majithia has also won awards for creative writing and participated in the prestigious Breadloaf writers’ workshop at Middlebury College in Vermont. Majithia has recently taught courses such as “Imaging India,” “The Postcolonial Turn,” “Global Traffic,” and “Melodrama and Modernity,” which reflect her disciplinary range.   At NYU Abu Dhabi, she teaches a core curriculum course in world literature, as well as courses on postcolonial literature and the cultures of globalization. Previously, she was an Andrew W. Mellon Teaching Fellow at the University of Pennsylvania and a visiting assistant professor of World Literature at the School of Humanities, Arts, and Cultural Studies at Hampshire College in Amherst, MA. Majithia earned her Ph.D. in Comparative Literature, with concentrations in feminist, gender, and sexuality studies and in South Asian studies from Cornell University, and her B.A. in English and Middle East and Asian Languages and Civilizations from Columbia University.
